Introduction:

Crime has proven to significantly influence the life pattern of people in a given community. Community life, people’s choice of work, living and shopping are actively impacted by this canker. Many research confirms that the rate of crime is highly centered in special or “hotspot” areas in cities. These active places have been reported to be the primary sources from where crimes spread throughout an entire city. Herein, we investigated the effects of these “hotspot” centers on the spread of crime in the city of Boston. Data from the Boston Police Department was collected and employed to develop a predictive model that evaluates the relationship between shootings and special locations in the city of Boston. The work is highly significant as it highlights the relevance of places in the decision making processes of robbers and other reported crimes. Knowledge of this information is bound to help all in the crime-fighting agencies including other stakeholders such as businessmen, landlords, and other employers with necessary information needed to combat and prevent crime in the city of Boston. This will go a long way to improve the culture and living of the people in the city.

Literature Review:

There exist several reviews investigating the relationship between city hotspot centers and their contribution to the growing crime rate. In 2004, a research team from the University of Maryland investigated crime incidents for 14 years at the level of street segments in Seattle. They found out consistently on a year-by-year basis that over 50 percent of crime in the City of Seattle was significantly concentrated in approximately 4.5 percent of street segments (Weisburd et al. 2004). These analyses revealed high crime stability in city hotspot centers over time. Furthermore, Braga et.al 2011 investigated the impact of hotspots on crime in the city of Boston. They highlighted that crime rates are highly concentrated in micro places and hotspots. Their finding suggests the need for concentrated efforts on specific places (hotspots) rather than increasing policing efforts for the whole city (Braga, Hureau, and Papachristos 2011). Several studied theories show that increased crime rates in communities are heavily linked to more alcohol outlets in these hotspot centers. Research confirms the complex relationship and association between alcohol outlet density and violent crimes. Also, further observations predict neighborhoods with increasing cases of violent crime rates were observed to be of lower income and in areas with less guardianship (Lipton, Yang, Braga, Goldstick, Newton, Rura 2012).

Research Questions:

There are several problems that we are hoping to address with this particular dataset on crime incidents in the Boston area. A question we would like to answer is if shootings are increasing in the Boston area. From there, we would like to better understand where the shootings are occuring in various areas across the city based on their district, street, even as detailed as their exact geographical location using latitude and longitude data. Once we have a better understanding of what the data looks like and is telling us, we would like to use this as a way to make inferences based on the data as to when and where we can expect shootings will occur. We are also interested in looking into if there is a correlation between the incident location (place where the shooting physically took place) and the reporting area (area where crime was reported from). With this model we would, in layman's terms, be able to “predict” shooting, although we are really just using the data to say “Based on this previous data, we can infer/expect shooting to increase/decrease this much over this amount of time and here is what types of crimes that involves. Along with the aforementioned, we hope to shed light on specific areas within Boston that have higher crime occurrences that may need more resources than other areas in the city in the future.

Data:

The data sources that we will be using for the project are the Crime Incident Reports from August 2015 - Current date. There are 8 reports, one for each year, and 18 columns in each. These reports are provided by the Boston Police Department of incidents that their officers attended to. These reports focus heavily on the location and time that a crime incident has occured. A more in-depth analysis of the dataset is included below in the crime incidents data dictionary. The data dictionary will explain each column in detail.
Column Name Column Description
_id A unique, numerical id number that is assigned to every case by the database that represents that specific case
INCIDENT_NUMBER Internal Boston Police Department report number
OFFENSE_CODE Numerical code of offense description
OFFENSE_CODE_GROUP Internal categorization of offense_description
OFFENSE_DESCRIPTION Primary descriptor of incident
DISTRICT What district the crime was reported in the city of Boston
REPORTING_AREA RA number associated with the where the crime was reported from
SHOOTING Indicated a shooting took place
OCCURED_ON_DATE Earliest date and time the incident could have taken place
YEAR Year incident took place
MONTH Month incident took place
DAY_OF_WEEK Day of the week incident took place (Monday, Tuesday, etc.)
HOUR Hour the incident took place
UCR_PART Universal Crime Reporting Part number (1,2,3)
STREET Street name the incident took place at in the city of Boston
Lat The latitude where the incident took place in the city of Boston
Long The longitude where the incident took place in the city of Boston
Location The latitude and longitude together marking the exact location where the incident occured in the city of Boston

Based on the columns above the crime incidents dataset deems appropriate for helping address our research questions about being able to predict locations of concern where crime incidents may be more likely to occur. The crime incidents reports include columns about the district, reporting area, street address, latitude, longitude, and location. The ability of having the exact location down to the latitude and longitude will allow our group to analyze very specific micro regions and allow the possibility of having a very accurate prediction of where crimes will occur. On top of having an accurate location the reports also have very precise data and times included. Columns such as occured_on_date, year, month, day_of_the_week, and hour will support our ability to predict at what days and times these crimes are occurring in these distinct locations. The reports allow us to possibly predict down to the minute where a crime may occur. Thus the crime incidents dataset provides an ideal source for helping address our research questions pertaining to where and when crime incidents are occuring in Boston.

Data Manipulation:

Upon importing 2015-2022 Boston crime incident reports into Python we found that our data was mainly qualitative or categorical variables. As we began cleansing the data we came across a lot of issues that would affect how we would use the data for visualization. The major issue though was in the 2015-2018 data they used OFFENSE_CODE_GROUP and UCR_PART but they did not in 2019-2022 and instead entered ‘None’ into the dataset. Due to this issus we decided the best course of action was to delete both of the columns from our dataset. The next issue that occurred was that in 2015-2018 data in the SHOOTING column they used Y to indicate there had been a shooting and NONE to indicate no shooting but in the 2019-2022 data they used 1 for yes and 0 for no. We had to reconfigure the entire SHOOTING column for 2015-2018 data to replace the Y and NONE with 1 and 0. We then went in to the Location column and got rid of the ‘(‘ and ‘)’ around the latitude and longitude.

The next issue that we ran into while manipulating the data was most of the data was qualitative data and wasn’t interval or ratio data. This made it hard to normalize the data and do principal component analysis as there were no numerical data types. We then created multiple frequency tables to evaluate the data. We found this to be the easiest method to analyze the data because it provided us with counts of each qualitative value. Below there are two frequency tables. One is OFFENSE_CODE and YEAR which shows us how many of a certain type of offence occurs in a particular year. The other frequency table shows how many certain types of offenses occur based on offense code occur at a certain hour of the day. As shown below is the data manipulation and cleansing that we did to prepare our data.

def bar_chart(list_number, list_unique):
    objects = list_unique
    y_pos = np.arange(len(objects))
    performance = list_number
 
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))    
    plt.bar(y_pos, performance, align='center', alpha=0.5)
    plt.xticks(y_pos, objects)
    plt.ylabel('Number') 
    plt.show()
    
    return 0

    list_number = list()
    
    while i < len(list_unique):
        list_number.append(len(CrimeAll.loc[CrimeAll[name_column] == list_unique[i]]))
        i += 1
    
    return list_unique, list_number

Summarize Findings

Based on our predictive modeling we have found that our best model is Gaussian Naive Bayers. The Gaussian Naive Bayers had an AUC of 0.6856671088540323 which was the highest out of all 6 models that we tuned.

For business improvement: Our visualizations shows us the hotspot centers for crime. Roxbury, Dorchestor, Southend, Downtown, Mattapan, South Boston and Brighton were observed to be most dangerous districts in the City of Boston, thus our visualization and predictive modeling of the BPD dataset provides stakeholders such as the Police Departments, Residents, landlords, business owners, government officials with ample information required for combating crime.

Police Department & Government Officials: We observed three categories for crime rates in the districts. That is, dangerous districts (Roxbury, Dorchestor, Southend, Downtown, Mattapan, South Boston and Brighton), moderately safe districts (Hyde Park and Jamaican Plain) and safe cities (West Roxbury, East Boston and Charlestown) with extremely low crime rates. Thus, the Police department and Government Officials are advised to channel more resources to the various hotspot centers.

Residents and Visitors: Residents of these hotspot centers are also advised to be alert at all times, move in groups, carry pepper sprays and other crime-combating tools permitted in the city. Visitors are therefore advised on the alarming crime rates expecially in the summer months and around the city's historical sites, thus they are advised to be very alert during the course of their visit.

Landlords and Business Owners: Landlords and business owners can use our visualizations to see where would be best to buy an apartment or business to avoid crime occuring at their business. This study also reveals that landlords and business owners in the hotspot centers in the City of Boston should consider the use of quality security systems when organizing apartments and their businesses.
